# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: 1889-cleveland-spiders-season
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:1889-cleveland-spiders-season/1887-cleveland-blues-season] The **1887 Cleveland Blues** baseball team finished with a 39–92 record, last in the American Association during their debut season.
[src:1889-cleveland-spiders-season/1887-cleveland-blues-season] Organized by streetcar tycoon Frank Robison, the team played its home games at National League Park.
[src:1889-cleveland-spiders-season/1888-cleveland-blues-season] The **1888 Cleveland Blues** baseball team finished with a 50–82 record, sixth place in the American Association.
[src:1889-cleveland-spiders-season/1889-boston-beaneaters-season] The **1889 Boston Beaneaters season** was the 19th season of the franchise.
[src:1889-cleveland-spiders-season/1889-boston-beaneaters-season] The team finished second in the National League.
[src:1889-cleveland-spiders-season/1889-brooklyn-bridegrooms-season] The **1889 Brooklyn Bridegrooms** won the American Association championship by two games over the St.
[src:1889-cleveland-spiders-season/1889-brooklyn-bridegrooms-season] The Bridegrooms played in the 1889 World Series representing the American Association against the New York Giants, champions of the National League.
[src:1889-cleveland-spiders-season/1889-brooklyn-bridegrooms-season] The Giants won the series, 6 games to 3.
[src:1889-cleveland-spiders-season/1889-brooklyn-bridegrooms-season] This series would be the first meeting between these two historic rivals.
[src:1889-cleveland-spiders-season/1889-chicago-white-stockings-season] The **1889 Chicago White Stockings season** was the 18th season of the Chicago White Stockings franchise, the 14th in the National League, and the fifth at the first West Side Park.
[src:1889-cleveland-spiders-season/1889-chicago-white-stockings-season] The White Stockings finished third in the National League with a record of 67–65.
[src:1889-cleveland-spiders-season/1889-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] The **1889 Cincinnati Red Stockings season** was a season in American baseball.
[src:1889-cleveland-spiders-season/1889-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] The team finished in fourth place in the American Association with a record of 76–63, 18 games behind the Brooklyn Bridegrooms.
[src:1889-cleveland-spiders-season/1889-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] The Red Stockings brought back manager Gus Schmelz for a third season in 1889, as he led the team to two straight seasons of 80 or more victories.
[src:1889-cleveland-spiders-season/1889-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] Cincinnati would have a new shortstop, signing local area player Ollie Beard to his first contract.
[src:1889-cleveland-spiders-season/1889-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] Cincinnati also signed rookie Bug Holliday, who would play in the outfield.
[src:1889-cleveland-spiders-season/1889-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] On the mound, another rookie, Jesse Duryea, would join the Red Stockings.
[src:1889-cleveland-spiders-season/1889-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] Bug Holliday had an excellent rookie season, hitting .321 with a league high nineteen home runs and a franchise record 104 RBI.
[src:1889-cleveland-spiders-season/1889-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] George Tebeau hit .252 with seven homers and 70 RBI, while scoring a team high 110 runs.
[src:1889-cleveland-spiders-season/1889-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] Hugh Nicol once again led Cincinnati in stolen bases, however, he failed to crack 100 for the first time since joining the team, as he stole 80 bases.
[src:1889-cleveland-spiders-season/1889-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] Jesse Duryea was the ace of the Red Stockings staff, going 32–19 with a 2.56 ERA in 53 games.
[src:1889-cleveland-spiders-season/1889-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] Lee Viau had a 22–20 record with a 3.79 ERA, while Tony Mullane was 11–9 with a 2.99 ERA.
[src:1889-cleveland-spiders-season/1889-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] Cincinnati began the season badly, as they lost their first four games, and were 5–10 in their first fifteen games.
[src:1889-cleveland-spiders-season/1889-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] The Red Stockings responded by going 16–6 in their next 22 games to climb into third place, however, the team lost their next seven games to fall under .500 once again and into sixth place.
[src:1889-cleveland-spiders-season/1889-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] Cincinnati would never be a factor in the pennant race, finishing in fourth place with a 76–63 record, eighteen games behind the Brooklyn Bridegrooms.
[src:1889-cleveland-spiders-season/1889-cleveland-spiders-season] Before the 1889 season, the Cleveland Blues switched from the American Association to the National League.
[src:1889-cleveland-spiders-season/1889-cleveland-spiders-season] They also earned a new nickname, the **Cleveland Spiders**, because so many of their players were very thin.
[src:1889-cleveland-spiders-season/1889-cleveland-spiders-season] They finished their first season in the National League with a 61–72 record, good enough for sixth place.
